title: Is NNN's 5.6% Dividend Yield Safe? A Beginner's Checklist
description: If you’re new to dividend investing, a 5.6% yield can look attractive—especially when it comes from a company that has raised its payout for 36 consecutive years. But yield alone doesn’t tell the full story. The question isn’t just “how much does it pay?” but “can it keep paying?”NNN REIT (NYSE:NNN) is a net lease real estate investment trust that owns 3,697 properties across all 50 U.S. states. Its tenants include convenience stores, auto service centers, and restaurants—businesses that sign long-term leases and pay rent month after month.But even stable-looking companies can cut dividends when the math stops working. This checklist walks through four metrics that help determine whether NNN’s dividend sits on solid ground—or shaky soil.What Is a Net Lease REIT?Before diving into the numbers, it helps to understand NNN’s business model.In a typical lease, landlords pay for property taxes, insurance, and maintenance. In a net lease, tenants pay those costs instead. This structure gives NNN predictable cash flows with minimal operating expenses—ideal for sustaining dividends.NNN’s tenants sign leases averaging 10.1 years in length, with built-in annual rent increases averaging 1.5%. This creates a long runway of predictable income, assuming tenants stay healthy.Now, let’s check the numbers.1. Credit Rating: BBB+ (S&P) / Baa1 (Moody’s)A credit rating measures a company’s ability to repay debt. Ratings of BBB- and above are considered “investment grade”—meaning institutional investors like pension funds and insurance companies can hold these bonds.NNN holds a BBB+ rating from S&P and Baa1 from Moody’s (latest publicly confirmed ratings). Both are solidly investment grade.Why does this matter for dividends? If a REIT’s rating falls below BBB-, two things happen:Borrowing costs rise sharplyMany institutional investors are forced to sellThis “forced selling” can trigger a downward spiral in stock price and make it harder for the company to raise capital. Dividend cuts often follow.NNN sits two notches above that BBB- cliff. It’s not a ...Full story available on Benzinga.com
